  "market_context": "Weekly chart printed a bullish candle 2 closure that failed and formed a bearish candle 2 closure, biasing price lower. Daily showed a V-shaped reversal / BPR with consolidation, setting up a swing trade short opportunity on BTC.",
  "key_observation": "When the hourly chart was too messy to read structure cleanly, the analyst moved up one timeframe to the 4-hour, which revealed a clean consolidation, V-shaped reversal, and continuation entry into the fair value gap.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the weekly, identified a failed bullish candle 2 closure followed by a bearish candle 2 closure, establishing a lower bias.",
    "Step 2: Dropped to the daily to locate a swing point aligned with the weekly bias — found a V-shaped reversal/BPR with consolidation.",
    "Step 3: Anticipated price to open, push higher to run swing-point liquidity, then trade lower; saw a large-wick reversal candle form.",
    "Step 4: Looked for hourly continuation — got a closure below the up-close candle series, entered short, and took 2R as price expanded.",
    "Step 5: Returned to the daily; expansion candle closed strongly, creating a new daily continuation setup with a fresh swing point.",
    "Step 6: Dropped to hourly for the next entry but found it messy, so moved up one timeframe to the 4-hour for clarity.",
    "Step 7: On the 4-hour, identified a clean consolidation and V-shaped reversal into a fair value gap; waited for closure below and a retracement.",
    "Step 8: Took the continuation entry on the retracement, targeting the lower swing point for 2R."
  ],
  "outcome": "Both example continuation entries reached 2R targets as price expanded lower.",
  "lessons": "Timeframe alignment does not have to be rigid — when the standard lower timeframe is messy, move up one timeframe to find cleaner structure. Trade candle-3 continuations rather than reversal candles for easier execution, always targeting at least 2R.",
